re, written across three decades but, for the most part, previously unavailable in English.More substantial than literary criticism, these essays collectively negotiate literature’s relation to philosophy. Nancy pursues such questions as literature’s claims to truth, the status of narrative, the relation of poetry and prose, and the unity of a book or of a text, and he addresses a number of major European writers, including Dante, Sterne, Rousseau, Hölderlin, Proust, Joyce, and Blanchot.The final section offers a number of impressive pieces by Nancy that completely merge his concerns for philosophy and literature and philosophy-as-literature. These include a lengthy parody of Valéry’s “La Jeune Parque,” several original poems by Nancy, and a beautiful prose-poetic discourse on an installation by Italian artist Claudio Parmiggiani that incorporates the Faust theme. Opening with a substantial Introduction by Jean-Michel Rabaté that elaborates Nancy’s importance as a literary thinker, this book constitutes the most substantial statement to date by one of today’s leading philosophers on a discipline that has been central to his work across his career.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aPhilosophy in literature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh  aBlanchot.  aClaudio Parmiggiani.  aHeidegger.  aHölderlin.  aPhilippe Lacoue-Labarthe.  aValéry.  acritical theory.  aliterary theory.  aphilosophy.1 aBononno, Robert.1 aRabaté, Jean-Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabaté, Jean-Michel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823277629zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823277